The point is, it’s easy with the benefit of hindsight, a basic understanding of

00:06:45.677 --> 00:06:51.207
mathematics, and all the evidence that we have today, it's easy to look back and

00:06:51.207 --> 00:06:57.637
say “how did anyone believe it was flat?”, but at the same time, it’s not so hard

00:06:57.817 --> 00:07:01.307
to understand why this might have been a tricky thing to get your head around.

00:07:02.437 --> 00:07:08.107
But, fast forward several thousand years, to the mid 19th century, it’s a

00:07:08.137 --> 00:07:12.507
bit harder to imagine why someone would believe the Earth was not round.

00:07:13.587 --> 00:07:19.757
Countless scientists and astronomers had proven it, map makers had charted much of the

00:07:19.757 --> 00:07:25.237
globe, we had a pretty robust understanding of gravity and of the movements of the planets.

00:07:26.307 --> 00:07:29.457
Debate over the shape of the Earth was almost

00:07:29.647 --> 00:07:33.757
non-existent, because there simply was nothing to debate.

00:07:33.937 --> 00:07:36.197
There was near unanimous agreement.

00:07:36.857 --> 00:07:37.667
It was round.

00:07:39.107 --> 00:07:45.287
But this all changed with the ideas of an Englishman called Samuel Rowbotham.

00:07:47.117 --> 00:07:53.947
He published a 16-page pamphlet in 1849 called Zetetic Astronomy, which was

00:07:53.957 --> 00:07:59.717
later turned into a book, and in it he proposed something revolutionary.

00:08:01.187 --> 00:08:05.347
According to Rowbotham, who was in fact writing under the pseudonym

00:08:05.707 --> 00:08:13.647
Parallax, the Earth was not a circular ball, but a pancake-shaped flat disc.

00:08:15.207 --> 00:08:21.917
This disc, according to Rowbotham, has the North Pole at its centre, the rest of the

00:08:21.917 --> 00:08:28.187
world going out from there, and at the edge of the world going all the way around,

00:08:28.437 --> 00:08:33.168
the crust of the pizza might be one way of thinking about it, there is Antarctica.

